This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it proposes a new defensive algorithm for deep neural networks. It also involves training procedures based on stochastic gradient descent, which is a common optimization method in machine learning. 

It is also likely to belong to cs.CV (Computer Vision) as the experiments are conducted on image datasets (CIFAR-10) and the neural network architecture used is VGG, which is commonly used in computer vision tasks. 

The paper may also belong to cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) as it addresses the vulnerability of deep neural networks in security-critical applications and proposes a defense technique against adversarial attacks. 

It may also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as it involves the use of deep neural networks, which is a common technique in AI research. 

Finally, it may belong to cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as it proposes a new ensemble technique for neural networks.
